body:
r? @pcwalton

(rust_highfive has picked a reviewer for you, use r? to override)

r? @brson 

cc @rust-lang/compiler - something to be aware of at least, and I may have updated something horribly incorrectly

@eddyb notes on [a comment from #23535](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/23535#issuecomment-109266575) that we may want to restrict the `ret void` change so that it is only injected on the switch injected in the generated drop-glue.
Apparently, LLVM PR23763 is fixed now.

@pnkfelix I think we're covered on that front because the function `iter_structural_ty` is only called from generating the drop glue.

@sanxiyn it has indeed! I'm testing out pulling in that revision and running tests now
@alexcrichton oh, of course, I forgot that. Maybe that machinery should be moved out of `trans::base` then (in the future).
Looks like https://github.com/rust-lang/llvm/commit/47dfcb7745766fee1aaa135a212b3e1f39d81e96 did indeed fix the problems I was seeing! Updated the LLVM submodule.

r=me once you've answered my q's.

This was a tough upgrade. Good work.
:umbrella: The latest upstream changes (presumably #25627) made this pull request unmergeable. Please resolve the merge conflicts.

Ok, the LLVM bug has not been fixed yet, and I had some time to do some more investigation. The end result was adding [this extra commit](https://github.com/rust-lang/llvm/commit/993e1fe0f6520dfbc9bc417d2a6ae62ea177df58) to the LLVM branch that we're using. Still running tests locally, but I suspect it will fix _that_ segfault at least.

re-r? @brson
Huh, I don't know where my comment went, but please add a comment to the source explaining the GOT issue so someone might be clued in to the need to revert it later.
